I hear ya talkin' about me!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I will freely admit Orion is a big sexy beast, but I happen to think there are bigger technological hurdles with it than most folks here are willing to acknowledge.<br>
<br>
By applying advances from other technical areas, we can make better designs now.  Orion has its own challenges, if we are going to tackle hurdles, we might as well go for a more solid solution.<br>
<br>
And for the inevitable &quot;better is the enemy of good&quot; commentary, show me the nuclear powered Orion prototypes that have tested the concept.<br>
<br>
To the best of my knowledge, the only testing ever performed on materials survival in close proximity was carbon coated iron spheres.  I suspect making a pusher plate survive is not as simple as we would like.<br>
<br>
One poster in a different thread mentioned an Orion pusher plate 135 feet in diameter only has to withstand 50,000 psi per pulse.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
ONLY?!   <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   That sounds like a doozy of a problem, folks.<br>
<br>
