<br>
Even if EPPP/NPR is developed, the development of high-power NEP like VASIMR is desirible for cargo due to the much higher Isp and cheaper fuel. Fusion test reactors have shown that superconducting magnets and hot plasma can coexist within a close proximity. And a 4MWe reactor, the size planned for the manned-scale VASIMR engine is hardly a stretch for modern reactor technology. No huge leaps are needed.<br>
<br>
As for the pusher plate issue, the plans as I have seen them involved the use of T-1 or similar steel. Better alloys exist today. If we just stuck a plate of steel out and shot a direction bomb at it, survival would be a hairy issue, but the plate is made in variable thicknesses proportional to the force recieved at that area. The plat also had shock absorbers directly connected to the plate which help aleiviate the displacement of the plate from the force of the impact. The artillery barrell is realy not a good analogy as the shapes are entirely different and that does play into the strength of the structure.  <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 79<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/24/02 12:36:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=197.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Nep systems such as Vasimir can perform as follows.]</span><hr size=1> 1 gram of mass expelled by a 200 MW vasimir<br>
can be expelled at 2,000,000 meters per<br>
 second. 1 gram is 1/454 th of a pound.<br>
2,000,000 meters per second is 6,000,000<br>
feet per second. 6,000,000 ft/sec * 1 pound<br>
of propellant = 6,000,000 pounds of thrust<br>
 6,000,000 /454 = 13,215 pounds of thrust<br>
2,000,000 meters/sec is a specific impulse<br>
of 200,000 seconds.<br>
<br>
Acceleration of the vehicle in terms of G=<br>
13,400 pounds / weight of vehicle in pounds.<br>
<br>
Example :For a a 6,000,000 pound <br>
vehicle G = 13,400 / 6,000,000<br>
* 32 feet per second.<br>
G = 10 meter per second in metric, or <br>
32 feet per second in  British imperial<br>
units.<br>
Here g = 2.33 * 10 to  -3 g /sec  for the above calculation<br>
Therefore  in 1 year you would gain  800 kilometers<br>
per second in in Delta v using above hypothethical<br>
Vasimir system<br>
800 kilometers per second = about 1,800,000<br>
miles an hour in velocity for one year of acceleration.<br>
<br>
The thrust of a rocket in pounds = the Exchaust<br>
 velocity of the rocket in feet per second *<br>
 the propellant mass flow rate in pounds per second.<br>
<br>
If you were using a a 200 kilowatt Vasimir system<br>
that heats 1 milligram of mass per second instead <br>
of a 200 megawatt Vasimir system that heats 1 gram of mass per second then devide the above figures of thrust and acceleration by 1000.<br>
For a mere 200 kilowatt  Vasimir that heats 1 milligram of mass per second the thrust would be 13.4 pounds, and the acceleration would be 2.33 * 10 to the -6 Gs for<br>
a 6,000,000 pound Vasimir driven  vessel.<br>
